 and in the ABC miniseries " War and Remembrance , " both of which aired in 1989 , and he was Henry L. Stimson , the 33rd U.S. president 's Secretary of War , in the 1995 HBO telefilm " Truman , " starring Gary Sinise . [CLS] [SEP] Similarly , he played the Secretary of Defense in " Meteor " ( 1979 ) . [CLS] [SEP] Most powerful people in N.Y. media . [CLS] [SEP] Dysart also performed extensively in the medical- ( movie ) field , performing enough doctor roles to , perhaps , qualify to practice . [CLS] [SEP] His two most memorable came in classic satires : in Paddy Chayevsky 's scathing " The Hospital " ( 1971 ) , starring George C. Scott ( a good friend ) , and in " Being There " ( 1979 ) , as Melvyn Douglas ' doctor . [CLS] [SEP] He also was a doctor who died a gruesome death in John Carpenter 's " The Thing " ( 1982 ) and a physician in such films as " The Terminal Man " ( 1974 ) , " The Falcon and the Snowman " ( 1985 ) and " Warning Sign " ( 1985 ) . [CLS] [SEP] Dysart portrayed J. Edgar Hoover in the 1993 USA telefilm " Marilyn & Bobby : Her Final Affair " and in Mario Van Peebles ' " Panther " ( 1995 ) . [CLS] [SEP] Dysart also excelled as cranky coots and shifty sorts . [CLS] [SEP] He portrayed a motel receptionist in Richard Lester 's " Petulia " ( 1968 ) ; was the bad guy who battled Clint Eastwood in " Pale Rider " ( 1985 ) ; stood out as a power player in Oliver Stone 's " Wall Street " ( 1987 ) ; and sold barbwire in " Back to the Future III " ( 1990 ) . [CLS] [SEP] Dysart was born March 30 , 1929 , in Boston and raised in Maine . [CLS] [SEP] Following high school , he attended the Gould Academy in Bethel , Maine , for a year , served in the U.S. Air Force and attended Emerson College , where he graduated with a master 's degree in speech communications . [CLS] [SEP] At the time , he was interested in a career in radio [CLS] [SEP] ( he became fascinated with the medium in first grade , when he was bedridden for a year because of rheumatic fever ) but was soon tempted by acting . [CLS] [SEP] He moved to New York on a whim and was able to land minor roles on TV and a part in an off - Broadway production of " The Iceman Cometh " opposite Jason Robards . [CLS] [SEP] In the mid-1960s , he joined the American Conservatory Theater and toured the country doing plays , then landed roles on Broadway in " All in Good Time , " " The Little Foxes " and " A Place Without Doors . " [CLS] [SEP] He received a Drama Desk Award for his performance in " That Championship Season . " [CLS] [SEP] Dysart 's credits include an eclectic array of movies , including " The Crazy World of Julius Vrooder " ( 1974 ) , " The Day of the Locust " ( 1975 ) , " The Hindenburg " ( 1975 ) , " An Enemy of the People " ( 1978 ) , " Prophecy " ( 1979 ) , " Mask " ( 1985 ) and " Hard Rain " ( 1998 ) . [CLS] [SEP] On television , he was top - notch in the telefilms [CLS] [SEP] " The Autobiography of Miss Jane Pittman " ( 1974 ) , " The People vs. Jean Harris " ( 1981 ) , as Dwight D. Eisenhower in " The Last Days of Patton " ( 1986 ) [CLS] [SEP] and as studio chief Louis B. Mayer in " Malice in Wonderland " ( 1985 ) . [CLS] [SEP] Survivors also include his stepson Arie and daughter - in - law Jeannine Jacobi , mother - in - law Lenore , brother and sister - in - law Nadine and John Jacobi and grandchildren Abby and Levi . [CLS] [SEP] A private memorial is being planned . [CLS] [SEP] In lieu of flowers , the family requests donations be made to the Will Geer Theatricum Botanicum , an outdoor theater in Topanga Canyon in the Los Angeles area . [CLS] [SEP] Dysart and Jacobi had a second home in the forests of British Columbia . [CLS] [SEP] He was lured out of retirement for his last onscreen appearance , the " L.A. Law " reunion telefilm of 2002 . [CLS] [SEP] " They remain timely , with cases about points of law that are still current , " he said of watching " L.A. Law " reruns in a 2002 interview with The Bangor Daily News . " [CLS] [SEP] [ The show ] was also